‘ We are asked fora song. Come, my lyre, if ever we have sung light strains that shall live, now raise a true Latin song, like those Alcaeus sang ‘of old. In war ancl shipwreck still he sang of wine and love. Sweet shell‚ beloved by Jove supreme, solace of toil, hear me when I duly call.’

This ode may have been written as a prelude of some serious ode or collection such as the first six of the third book, to which ‘Latinum carmen’ may refer. Horace quotes his great model to show that songs oflove and wine are not inconsistent with serious poetry. Metre, 69.
